        <name>37.1.1.5 General permutation take r at a time</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p&gt;In general the numbers of permutations of &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(n\)&lt;/span&gt; objects taken &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(r\)&lt;/span&gt; at a time is &lt;br&gt;\(\qquad n(n-1)(n-2)\dots (n-r+1)\qquad \) which is the same as \(\displaystyle{\quad\frac{n!}{(n-r)!}}\)
&lt;br&gt;This is usually denoted by &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(^nP_r\)&lt;/span&gt; so that&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\[\displaystyle{\qquad ^nP_r=\frac{n!}{(n-r)!}}.\]&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;If we allow repetitions the number of permutations becomes &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(n^r\)&lt;/span&gt; (can you see why?).&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
